1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,400
Before we dive into the transformer architecture,

2

00:00:03,400  -->  00:00:06,340
we need to talk about the softmax function,

3

00:00:06,340  -->  00:00:11,000
since we will use it in a few places when we will implement our model.

4

00:00:11,000  -->  00:00:13,720
An important observation is that an output of

5

00:00:13,720  -->  00:00:18,460
a neural network layer can contain pretty much any numerical values.

6

00:00:18,460  -->  00:00:22,140
These raw output values are also called logits.

7

00:00:22,140  -->  00:00:25,040
In some cases, we need to convert logits

8

00:00:25,040  -->  00:00:29,440
produced by a model into a probability distribution.

9

00:00:29,510  -->  00:00:33,610
To create a probability distribution from logits,

10

00:00:33,610  -->  00:00:39,320
we need to make sure that every logit value will be converted into a value from

11

00:00:39,320  -->  00:00:47,035
0-1 and that the sum of all result values should be equal to 1.

12

00:00:47,035  -->  00:00:53,070
A common way to do this is to use the softmax function. Here is how it works.

13

00:00:53,070  -->  00:00:57,690
When we want to convert logit to the probabilities, for every logit,

14

00:00:57,690  -->  00:01:04,825
we need to take this logit value and raise e to the power of this logit value.

15

00:01:04,825  -->  00:01:11,775
We have e^1.2, e^1.4, and so on.

16

00:01:11,775  -->  00:01:14,885
Raising e, a positive number,

17

00:01:14,885  -->  00:01:18,310
to any power will give us a positive number,

18

00:01:18,310  -->  00:01:23,910
and we've immediately satisfied the first requirement making all outputs positive.

19

00:01:23,910  -->  00:01:29,850
Now, how do we make sure that all output values of the softmax function sum up to one?

20

00:01:29,850  -->  00:01:34,460
To do this, we first compute the sum of all these values we've got so

21

00:01:34,460  -->  00:01:40,280
far that we write in this shorter mathematical notation.

22

00:01:40,280  -->  00:01:42,360
Then having this sum,

23

00:01:42,360  -->  00:01:46,500
we need to divide each value by the value of this sum.

24

00:01:46,500  -->  00:01:51,540
This will make sure that the sum of result values will be equal to one.

25

00:01:51,540  -->  00:01:55,560
That's it. That's how we compute the softmax function.

26

00:01:55,560  -->  00:01:59,580
Now, once you are familiar with how softmax is calculated,

27

00:01:59,580  -->  00:02:04,960
it will be easier to understand the mathematical notation, which looks like this.

28

00:02:04,960  -->  00:02:06,920
Where for every output value,

29

00:02:06,920  -->  00:02:13,940
we calculate the exponents and divide each one of them by the sum of all exponents.

30

00:02:14,240  -->  00:02:17,280
The output of the softmax function is

31

00:02:17,280  -->  00:02:22,215
a probability distribution that we can represent using a histogram.

32

00:02:22,215  -->  00:02:25,580
Softmax function has some interesting properties.

33

00:02:25,580  -->  00:02:29,120
If one input value is much larger than the rest,

34

00:02:29,120  -->  00:02:32,320
softmax will return a probability that is

35

00:02:32,320  -->  00:02:36,640
significantly higher than probabilities for other outputs.

36

00:02:36,640  -->  00:02:43,380
In this case, softmax returns 0.9 for the largest value in the input.

37

00:02:43,380  -->  00:02:45,920
For all the smaller logit values,

38

00:02:45,920  -->  00:02:49,740
it will return probabilities that are close to zero.

39

00:02:49,740  -->  00:02:53,720
If there are several logits with similar values,

40

00:02:53,720  -->  00:02:59,240
softmax will return similar probability values for each one of them.
